Let's verify escaping:
`\\d` -> `\d` in regex
`\\s` -> `\s` in regex
`\\+` -> `\+` in regex (though `+` doesn't need escaping inside `[]`, it's fine)
`\\-` -> `\-` in regex (hyphen inside `[]` should be escaped or at start/end to be literal, `\\-` is fine)
`\\.` -> `\.` in regex
`\\(` -> `\(` in regex
`\\)` -> `\)` in regex
So `[^\\d\\s\\+\\-\\.\\(\\)]` is correct.

Actually, to be safer and avoid regex pitfalls, I'll just iterate and check characters manually. It's more robust and doesn't rely on regex escaping nuances.

```java
class PhoneNumber {
    private final String number;

    PhoneNumber(String numberString) {
        StringBuilder digits = new StringBuilder();
        for (char c : numberString.toCharArray()) {
            if (Character.isLetter(c)) {
                throw new IllegalArgumentException("Letters not permitted");
            }
            if (!Character.isDigit(c) && !isAllowedPunctuation(c)) {
                throw new IllegalArgumentException("Punctuations not permitted");
            }
            if (Character.isDigit(c)) {
                digits.append(c);
            }
        }

        String cleanNumber = digits.toString();

        if (cleanNumber.length() == 11) {
            if (cleanNumber.charAt(0) == '1') {
                cleanNumber = cleanNumber.substring(1);
            } else {
                throw new IllegalArgumentException("11 digits must start with 1");
            }
        }

        if (cleanNumber.length() != 10) {
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("Incorrect number of digits");
        }

        if (cleanNumber.charAt(0) < '2') {
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("Area code cannot start with zero or one");
        }
        if (cleanNumber.charAt(3) < '2') {
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("Exchange code cannot start with zero or one");
        }

        this.number = cleanNumber;
    }

    private boolean isAllowedPunctuation(char c) {
        return c == ' ' || c == '+' || c == '-' || c == '.' || c == '(' || c == ')';
    }

    String getNumber() {
        return number;
    }
}
```

